@paper-source /home/joe/npt/paper-v2.3/paper_v2.3.html
@merge-policy Preserve the canonical backward-propagation account while retaining the paper variant's commons-governance rule, workload evidence, author-credit mechanism, and light-touch review cycle.

! conclusion: Materials stay current and trusted only when local adaptation flows back into a stewarded commons. Open licensing is not enough. The programme needs an upstream channel, author credit for adapters, and a light-touch review rule - every adaptation used more than once is shared - so local learning becomes shared infrastructure rather than invisible private labour.
  + context: A programme provides high-quality training materials that trainers praise, adapt, and maintain informally. Materials age, local settings differ, and each adaptation is a learning event. In NPT terms this is Collective Action 3.2 Relational Integration and 3.4 Contextual Integration: maintaining connections between materials, trainers, and programme. In Ostrom terms this is a knowledge-commons stewardship problem. In whole-board-play terms, Patterns 1 and 2 gave the agent the rules and conditions to play; this pattern asks whether what is learned from play can update the shared structure.
  + IF:
    Trainers are developing local competence through iterative delivery. Each local adaptation discovers something about what works in a setting, what fails, and what should be added, removed, or resequenced. If those adaptations can flow back, future trainers inherit a better resource and aggregate maintenance work falls.
  + HOWEVER:
    No upstream channel exists. Trainers rework materials independently; adaptations stay local; the "gold standard" reputation erodes as content drifts from practice. Maintenance falls to whoever notices a problem: ad hoc, unrecognised work on top of constrained time. Open licensing was planned but stewardship infrastructure was not built. Workload and capacity concerns are the most prevalent corpus theme (34 of 134 turns, 25%), and the COM-B item "policies, procedures, and resource allocation are appropriate" is below midpoint (M=3.78). This is like a learning system that plays games but never updates its weights.
  + THEN:
    The programme establishes open licensing plus an active upstream channel, a light-touch review cycle, and a shared rule: every adaptation used more than once is shared, with the adapter credited as author. Contributing is made no harder than consuming. Local groups catalogue assets, a community of practice shares adaptations, and named reviewers steward the syllabus. The shift is from individual burden to community infrastructure.
  + BECAUSE:
    NPT: Relational Integration depends on trust in the people and materials the practice uses; Contextual Integration depends on fit with the institutional context. Invisible rework breaks both.

    Sen: Usable materials sustain capability beyond the initial event, but capability develops through use. If adaptations cannot flow back, the capability gain remains private and the commons degrades.

    Whole-board play: Backward propagation from local play into shared structure is what distinguishes a system that learns from a system that merely runs. The training programme's "weights" are its materials, syllabus, and practical knowledge.

    Ostrom: A knowledge commons requires rules matched to local conditions. "Every adaptation used more than once is shared, credited as author" is lightweight, low-cost, and aligned with the value trainers already create.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Establish open licensing with an active upstream pathway
    - Adopt the rule: every adaptation used more than once is shared
    - Credit adapters as authors so invisible labour becomes visible contribution
    - Implement a light-touch review cycle with named reviewers
    - Make contributing as frictionless as consuming
    - Surface aggregate labour: count contributions, reviews, and accepted changes
    - Test: can a local adaptation reach the shared repository within one cycle?
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    Local adaptations can flow back into the shared materials through a defined light-touch review cycle. Adapters are credited as authors. The upstream pathway is no harder than the downstream consumption pathway, and the materials commons has active stewardship beyond the original author.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - No backward propagation: local learning stays local and shared weights never update
    - No upstream channel: local adaptations cannot reach the commons
    - Licensing without stewardship: open licence exists but no one curates or reviews
    - Invisible rework: maintenance is unrecognised work that compounds overload
    - Ad hoc sharing: slides appear informally without a reliable curation path
    - Drifting gold standard: reputation persists while practice diverges
    - Content drift: materials age without systematic review
  + ANCESTORS:
    - Paper v2.3, Pattern 3: Shared Maintenance
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T1 ("a gold standard of how to run an intro to reproducible research session")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T1 ("every time I've done it, I haven't given enough time")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T1 ("a couple of colleagues have uploaded their slides")
    - Corpus theme: workload/capacity, 34 of 134 turns (25%)
    - COM-B: "policies, procedures, and resource allocation are appropriate" M=3.78
    - REDF proposal: permissive licensing was planned; stewardship infrastructure was not
    - Ostrom (1990): rules matched to local conditions
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from NPT Collective Action 3.2 Relational Integration and 3.4 Contextual Integration.
    Tier: Intervention. Coordination: Medium, expressed as community norm rather than a single organisational decision.
    Implementation-mode link: unshared rework is a defining signature of absorbed input.
    Canonical deepening: backward propagation and co-evolution of resource and users.
    Paper-specific mechanism: light-touch review, author credit, and the "adaptation used more than once" rule.
